# Project initialisation

Run these three checks at the **start of every new conversation**, before doing any other work.

## 1 â€” Ensure todo files exist

Check whether all three task board files exist:

- `.ai/todo/todo.md`
- `.ai/todo/someday.md`
- `.ai/todo/todo.archive.md`

If any are missing, create them immediately with this content:

| File | Opening line |
|------|-------------|
| `todo.md` | `# Active tasks` |
| `someday.md` | `# Someday / backlog` |
| `todo.archive.md` | `# Archive` |

Tell the user which files were created. If all three exist, say nothing â€” do not announce it.

## 2 â€” Check GitHub config

Check whether `.ai/config/project.json` exists.

- **If it exists:** read it silently and proceed.
- **If it is missing:** tell the user:
  > "GitHub is not configured for this project. Ask me to run the GitHub setup and I will walk you through connecting a new or existing repository."
  Then wait â€” do not start any other task until the user either runs the setup or explicitly says to skip it.

### GitHub setup flow (when user requests it)

Ask in order:
1. "Is this a **new** GitHub repository or an **existing** one?"
2. **New:** "What would you like to name the repository?" + "What is your GitHub username?"
   **Existing:** "Paste the full GitHub repository URL:" + "Confirm your GitHub username:"
3. Write `.ai/config/project.json`:
   ```json
   {
     "github": {
       "repo_url": "https://github.com/<username>/<repo>",
       "username": "<username>"
     }
   }
   ```
   Create `.ai/config/` if it does not exist.
4. Run:
   ```bash
   git init 2>/dev/null || true
   git remote get-url origin 2>/dev/null && git remote set-url origin <repo_url> || git remote add origin <repo_url>
   ```
5. Confirm to the user: config saved, remote set, password will be asked before every push.

**Security rule:** never save a password, token, or PAT to any file â€” not `.ai/config/project.json`, not anywhere.

## 3 â€” PAT required before every git push

**Never run `git push` directly.** Before any push:

1. Ask the user: "Please provide your GitHub PAT (Personal Access Token) to push now."
2. Read `.ai/config/project.json` to get `username` and `repo_url`.
3. Push using:
   ```
   git push https://<username>:<PAT>@<repo_url_without_https://>
   ```
   Example: if `repo_url` is `https://github.com/alice/my-project`, run:
   ```
   git push https://alice:<PAT>@github.com/alice/my-project.git
   ```
4. Do **not** save the PAT anywhere. Use it for this push only.

If the user has not run GitHub setup yet (no `.ai/config/project.json`), complete check 2 first.
